===Etymology===
* First attested in the late 14th century.
* From {{etyl|enm}} {{term|abissus|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|LL.}} {{term|abyssus||a bottomless gulf|lang=la}}, from {{etyl|grc}} {{term|sc=polytonic|ἄβυσσος||tr=abyssos|bottomless|lang=grc}}, from {{term|sc=polytonic|ἀ-||tr=a-|not|lang=grc}}+ {{term|sc=polytonic|βυσσός||tr=bysso|depth|lang=grc}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{rhymes|ɪs}}
* {{enPR|ə-bĭs'}}, {{IPA|/ə.ˈbɪs/}} {{X-SAMPA|/@"bIs/}}
* {{audio|en-us-abyss.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|es}}

# A bottomless or [[unfathomed]] depth, gulf, or [[chasm]]; hence, any deep, [[immeasurable]].
# [[hell|Hell]]; the [[bottomless pit]]; [[primeval]] [[chaos]].
# [[infinite|Infinite]] time; a vast intellectual or moral depth.
# {{context|heraldry}} The center of an [[escutcheon]].

====Quotations====
* {{seeCites}}

====Usage notes====
This word, in its leading uses, is associated with the [[cosmological]] [[notions]] of the Hebrews, having reference to an {{term|illimitable}} mass of waters from which our earth [[sprung]], and beneath whose [[profound]] depths the wicked were [[punished]].

